50|$|Following {{damage caused}} by a {{windstorm}} in 1933 the rear verandah was enclosed and extended and the kitchen built in its present location. At about this time the originally corrugated iron gabled roof was also replaced by a corrugated iron hipped roof. In about 1942 an air raid shelter was excavated {{to the east of}} the rear of the house, but there is now no clear above ground evidence of this feature. Another notable feature of the house is the use of laced <b>hoop</b> <b>iron</b> to provide screening for the verandah. The <b>hoop</b> <b>iron</b> was originally used at the wool scour to bind wool bale packs and wool bales. Townspeople found the material ideal to create shaded semi-enclosed verandahs. The technique was once seen on most Ilfracombe houses, but now survives only at the Langenbaker house.|$|E
